  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 11-17.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - The tribe of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Gad",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is taken next, and occupies but few lines. Gad was born seventh in order of all the sons of Jacob (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 30:9-12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and first of the children of Leah's maid Zilpah. The compiler seems to pass easily on to Gad, from the mere circumstance of the name of the tribe being so constantly linked with that preceding, in the matter of local settlement on the east of Jordan, after the journeyings of the wilderness (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 13:7, 8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The geography in vers. 11 and 16 offers very little difficulty. Compared with the time of the first settling of the Gadites (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:10-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 13:25, 30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), it is evident that they had pushed their borders further to the north, trenching somewhat upon the lot of the half-tribe Manasseh, as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "they",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " also in turn extended their limits northward to Hermon (ver. 23). This reconciles ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 13:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " with the present passage. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Salcah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or (Authorized Version) Salchah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 13:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), is probably to be identified as the modern ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Sulkhad",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", at the extreme eastern point of the plain ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Hauran",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which is bordered by the desert. \"In Gilead in Bashan\" may be read, with some, as two coordinate places, separating them by a stop; or may point to a time when Bashan included the upper half of Gilead. Sharon, which Keil, quoting Reland, 'Pal. Ill.,' 370, would make the well-known Sharon of Carmel and the Mediterranean, is, though unmentioned elsewhere, probably distinguished sufficiently from it by the absence of the article, which is invariably prefixed to the other. Stanley's suggestion ('Sinai and Palestine,' edit. 1866, pp. 484, 485, 260) would seem exceedingly apt, that it is one in fact, as one in derivation and meaning, with the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Mishor",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " \"level ]ands,\" \"table-land\") of Gilead and Bashan. With this explanation, however, the term \"suburbs\" does not so well agree. Upon the other side, distant as the well-known Sharon is, a link of connection might be found with it, in that the other Manasseh half-tribe stretched into its plains; and in that case the last word of the verse, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "תּועְאותָם",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", might mean (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 17:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") \"the outgoings\" of the land or regions in question to the \"sea\"-coast. 1 Chronicles 5:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The families of the tribe of Gad, and their dwelling-places. - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 5:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In connection with the preceding statement as to the dwelling-places of the Reubenites, the enumeration of the families of Gad begins with a statement as to their dwelling-places: \"Over against them (the Reubenites) dwelt the Gadites in Bashan unto Salcah.\" Bashan is used here in its wider signification of the dominion of King Og, which embraced the northern half of Gilead, i.e., the part of that district which lay on the north side of the Jabbok, and the whole district of Bashan; cf. on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Salcah formed the boundary towards the east, and is now Szalchad, about six hours eastward from Bosra (see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
